snippet.textDisplay: My father was an Aero Space Engineer for Lockheed Martin. His job was top secret so I was never fully able to know what he did, but he did tell me that he was working on space shuttle tiles. I was allowed to visit his workplace once and I'll never forget the padlock that was attached to his desk drawer. There was a HUGE lock that had three different dials on it! Three different passwords to open one drawer, wow, lol. That was security back then and it was no joke. I was able to hold a tile in my hand and was amazed as to how light it was. Its composition was almost like a strange drywall, but WAY lighter and with micro holes in it. Hard to explain, but I can brag and say I held one and that I'm so proud of my dad. He passed away at 82 years old on April 25, 2001. He missed 9/11, he missed the shuttles being docked, and he's missing out on SpaceX and these amazing rockets that are able to return to Earth and land on a platform. I miss him so much, and writing this makes me cry. I would give anything to see his face be in awe while he watched this video. I'm sure he would be thinking that he played a part in getting that rocket up thru the sky. Thank you so much for this video, it meant a lot to me. Good luck on future travels, I'll be watching. :)

snippet.textDisplay:
Spacex is a great deal even when they use their booster just once. Then to reuse it just once, that second time, basically it's the cost of the fuel and oxidizer, and a checkup of the hardware. Now it's a purpose built vehicle that can be used ten times. Meanwhile ULA and everyone else is throwing their hardware away after one use.
Blue Origin's New Glenn will be following this mode of reuse once it gets going. New Shepard is just a hardware development vehicle at best. Rocket Labs is already cheap but their first stage reuse means they can scale up their launches. The Chinese saw the light and there's a private company doing the landing bit development first. Be interesting to see how far they get.
Roscosmos has to be thinking about this. The Soyuz is a very hardy bit of Russian engineering but it's a one use vehicle. Meanwhile Spacex's only one-time use part of their entire stack is the second stage. Everything else has been re-flown multiple times. No way Roscosmos can compete with the Soyuz once crew Dragon gets going.

Why don't we do something where we all get paid as we progress towards colonizing Mars?

DanielHall4Freedom
Think Harder Politics MATH

I'm trying to see that lots of people can afford to go to Mars when the time comes.

I know of this company called Global Domains International.

The product they provide is instantaneous online.

They pay us as we refer customers to them.

They pay us ongoing monthly commissions.

Since it's domain names we acquire from them, and since it costs just $10 a month, and they pay out 50% to the network we each grow by each of us just referring a few, we can easily go VIRAL if we each just create our usernames and domain names in the pattern of

OurName4Freedom
or
OurName4Mars

Freedom Dividends is the big news Andrew Yang is making more and more popular.

We all already have our given name. We simply add 4Freedom to them or 4Mars if we want to be that focused.

We're showing how the high-tech of Internet can pay us too, not just pay the big guys on top (Jeff Bezos and the like).

For us we're showing, by owning, OurName4Freedom or OurName4Mars and .ws for us the meaning is
Wholesome Society or
We Spacefarers (so it's where the little folk like average folk) all get a piece of the action as well.

Our work is to pay (the little it costs: $10 a month) to create and own:
OurName4Freedom . ws (Note: the company (GDI host William Shatner on our site) or
OurName4Mars, in my case DanielHall4Freedom . ws

Using the sites the company ((GDI) immediately provides us)) we invite others we know who are of like mind to go to our .ws to create TheirName4Freedom . ws
or TheirName4Mars.

We each invite just a few. It multiplies... Goes Viral.

We're all better off and we're all supporting the goals we're interested in.

WS
